posts.com:
>>114427352
To grossly oversimplify, the two most important notes in a chord are usually the bottom and the top note, those are what your listener is going to be drawn to unless there’s something deliberately drawing their attention to another note
With “big” chords, you don’t have a lot of control over this, because you’re playing over 5-6 strings and thus your chord choices are reduced down dramatically to “what notes can my monkeys hand reach that don’t clash”
With triads, you only have 3 strings to worry about, so you have a lot more options that fit into your hand and thus you can play around with a lot more voicing options
So it’s not enough to learn “the standard triads” like you can cowboy chords, you really need to learn the various voicing of the same triads and how they interact
Hope this helps

>downside of set neck guitars is you can't fix the neck angle so if yours is off you might never be able to achieve good action
Used buyers guide if you're concerned about this:
Contact the seller and ask for two closup pictures:
One with a ruler measuring the action at the 12th
One of the bridge from the side
If action is medium high and the bridge is already near bottomed out, don't buy that guitar. If there is plenty of room for the saddles to move down, it's fine. Keep in mind with tune-o-matic bridges you need the tailpiece a certain amount lower than the bridge to create appropriate break angle over the saddles.

If you never practice with a metronome or do exercises specifically to improve your rhythm it shouldn't be a surprise when you 'challenge' yourself to play with one and find it difficult. You could spend several lifetimes on rhythm alone and still find ways to improve. The 'simplest' quarter note rhythm can be played on an infinite continuum of skill levels, the better you get the more microrhythmic detail you can perceive in the placement of each quarter note. You can tell a great deal about someone musicality just from hearing them clap quarter notes.

Try and count out loud to EVERYTHING you practice, your voice is the key. It has to be out loud ,not just in your head. If you can't count 1 2 3 4 (or whatever meter) at the same time as playing a rhythm then you don't know the rhythm.

I can't count how much I've have this album on repeat. I've never had a favorite like it. The last time I did this, I was 10 and only had 1 cd for my cd player. I hope it's multipart and this was the first.

Nobody ever made an album like it. Even when Elvis did Christian albums, it was always covers.

These are catchy original hi-fi tracks that will make you nod your head and hit the repeat button for more.

The content is about the struggle with the self in the greater context of God's creation as a flawed man. In effect, this is a continuation of Jesus Walks.

Every track is a pleasant surprise. Use This Gospel is one of my favorites, but that's not to say that the others aren't as good.

If you never took the time for it, grab a glass of wine, dim the lights, and enjoy. This is the best album I've ever heard.

posts.name: Anonymous

>>114436943
For a start, "performing live" and "DJing live" mean different things when it comes to electronic music.
A live set is usually a performance of the musician's own material, sequenced in such a way to allow for the musician to trigger certain elements of the track on the fly
A DJ set is usually a mix of tracks from which the DJ pulls from, usually produced by other musicians but can contain some original material, where the "live" element comes from the transition between the tunes and the track selection.

>>114402252
the thing about making sample based beats especially if you're trying to do the 90s boom bap feel is that in terms of melody there is only ever slight variation on a main motif and maybe another element or two for a hook but those would be high passed and eating up very little of the main part of the mix. the way you keep a beat interesting is by throwing in a bunch of unique sounds and textures that play only once or maybe twice throughout the beat once you have it laid out. it takes less effort than you think and once you get the hang of it you can start using it to really build and accentuate energy as opposed to just making things less repetitive.
doing the whole a/b/c verse/chorus/bridge with unique progression for each is not the type of sectioning you tend to see in hip hop.

>>114406121
I work on more than one project, maybe 10 or so.
I just go with the flow, look into this project or the other project. Do what i enjoy right now, either build a pattern, play around with synth, make a melody or play with some effects. Or i start a new project.

There are at least 2 dozen new tracks, but keep myself only active on 8 to 10 tracks. I can finish a track on one day, 8 hours max. Sometimes i produce into the night and when i wake up the next morning i finish the track. But i also have tracks i don't want to finish, i keep them in the production stage on purpose just for fun.

Thats the thing right here, do not start your daw with the expectation to finish a song. Start it with a different intend, see what direction this goes, save it and keep it for later use, or just build some presets for a random vst, make your own samples, etc etc etc....

the panning is as if you have just discovered that stereo audio exists; not only do you not need to hardpan stuff, but anything below, say, 150 hz (but probably more, say 300 hz or something) should be completely mono. stereo imaging on low frequency stuff should be avoided. the sidechaining is fine, it's stylistic so i won't make any value judgment, but you could probably afford a faster release on it. also re: the fact that elements in the R channel are sidechained to elements (the kick) that aren't in the R channel literally at all is extremely jarring. the percussion needs to brought waaay up in the mix, it is almost completely lost atm. bring it up in the mix and add some parallel compression to it. i think you could also crank some saturation on the kick/bass elements... really everything, to be honest. neat track, but needs a lot of love in the mixing department.

I also only use midi drums. I'm still pretty new to making them sound realistic. The one I dropped isn't my best example of drums but using realistic drum samples is only half the battle. Velocity is really important, but so is mixing (I mix kick, snare, toms, cymbals, and then a fake overhead all separate). Depending on the song I might also master the drums with a bit of reverb. Making the sample sound realistic really does boil down to mixing each drum track well. ALSO, don't quantize the track. Adding a very, very slight amount of random swing will make the track sound more like a human is playing it (due to the slight error). I'm still not anywhere close to being great at mixing midi drums, but those are the tips I have learned so far.

Vaporwave is a unique and innovative genre of electronic music that has pushed the boundaries of what music can be. Its use of slowed-down, chopped-up samples of 1980s and 1990s pop music creates a surreal, nostalgic atmosphere that is unlike anything else in the music world. Its commentary on consumer culture and the nostalgia of the digital age is both thought-provoking and relatable, and its incorporation of visual elements such as glitch art and retro computer graphics adds an extra layer of depth to the music. In addition, the genre has been influential in the development of other styles of electronic music, making it a crucial part of the musical landscape. Overall, vaporwave's unique sound and cultural significance make it a standout among other genres of music.

>"I'd Have You Anytime" is a song written by George Harrison and Bob Dylan, released in 1970 as the opening track of Harrison's first post-Beatles solo album, All Things Must Pass. The pair wrote the song at Dylan's home in Bearsville, near Woodstock in upstate New York, in November 1968. Its creation occurred during a period when Harrison had outgrown his role in the Beatles and Dylan had withdrawn from the pressures of fame to raise a family. "I'd Have You Anytime" is recognised as a statement of friendship between the two musicians, whose meetings from 1964 onwards resulted in changes in musical direction for both Dylan and the Beatles. The song reflects the environment in which it was written, as Harrison's verses urge the shy and elusive Dylan to let down his guard, and the Dylan-composed choruses respond with a message of welcome.

Eastern Youth's self-titled is honestly one of the best in the entire genre:
https://youtu.be/E8pMtwtyfG0

Before going onto international notoriety and opening for big bands like Jimmy Eat World, At the Drive-In and Cursive, Hokkaido's Eastern Youth shook up the Japanese underground as part of the emerging Samurai Spirits Skinheads scene. Unlike many of their contemporaries who took influence from the British and American skinhead scenes that subsequently incorporated various Rock influences, Eastern Youth's inspiration grew from Washington DC's Post-Hardcore scene along with various Oi! and Street Punk bands. The music here sounds as inspired by Fugazi or Rites of Spring as they do by Angelic Upstarts or Combat 84. Jangly, energetic riffs buzzing with angst and alienation guide the album from track to track at a charged tempo that only relents on a handful of tracks while still keeping the wattage at full force. The memorable choruses have enough simplicity to break the language barrier and allow plenty of non-speakers to sing along after repeated listens.

Tried to listen it for the first time back in 2010, I was 14-15 at that time and I had heard good things about it from prog rock fans (which is was into back then), listened to it again in 2017 after listening to a bunch of music, I was very into 90s psychedelic rock at the time, Moonlight on Vermont immediately struck me as an incredible song I couldn't believe was conceived in 1969, then listened to the entire thing. While I could appreciate where it came from I couldn't dive in it freely. It was a couple of years later after listening to a lot of Mothers of Invention that I could listen to it, on repeat and even casually listen to a bunch of songs on it. It really is a hard one to digest. I was on the "I know it's good but I think it's more of a meme" side for too long, and I think most of the people who see it that way have still a lot of (rock) music to listen to.

So it's a good video but it basically just confirms that the album is highly advanced and complex shitposting. I mean just because you can describe the music in complex musical terms as a mish mash of different tonalities and rhythms doesn't mean it's good music. I could write a computer program that shits out frownland like music by just randomly generating melodies in different keys and time signatures and then stitching them together. It's not an amazing musical achievement to have made something like this.

I mean don't get me wrong, the fact that a group of people actually spent months learning this madness and were able to perform it consistently is incredible and it's a very interesting novelty album in that sense. But musically it's not that impressive. In fact the algorithmic process I described is basically how it was composed, except instead of a program it was beefheart coming up with random repeating phrases and french stitching them together. The end result isn't really musically any more interesting than the random process.
